"""
MKT Context Commentary — Revelation chapters 21–22
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-revelation-21-22.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/revelation.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/revelation.json (MKT text)

Key decisions in this range:
- New Jerusalem: Ezek 40-48 + Isa 60 as primary OT templates; city-as-Holy-of-Holies via
  12,000-stadia cube echoing the 20-cubit cube of Solomon's Holy of Holies (1 Kgs 6:20)
- Breastplate stones (vv. 19-20): listed as background without adjudicating stone identifications
- No temple (v22): contextualizes the entire OT temple trajectory toward direct divine presence
- River of life (22:1-2): Ezek 47 + Eden (Gen 2) as co-templates for restored creation
- Maranatha (22:20): Aramaic liturgical formula from early church Lord's Supper practice
- "Do not seal" (22:10): directly contrasted with Daniel 12:4 sealing command
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

REVELATION = {
  "21": {
    "1": '<p>The vision of "a new heaven and a new earth" is the direct fulfillment of Isa 65:17 ("Behold, I create new heavens and a new earth, and the former things shall not be remembered or come into mind") and Isa 66:22 ("the new heavens and the new earth that I make shall remain before me, declares the LORD"). This is the culminating OT promise of a creation-wide renewal, not merely the restoration of one nation. The disappearance of "the sea" has specific cosmological weight: in ancient Near Eastern cosmology shared across Mesopotamia, Canaan, and the Hebrew world, the sea (<em>thalassa</em>, Hebrew <em>yam</em>) represented the primordial chaos, the domain of threatening monsters (Gen 1:2; Job 7:12; Ps 74:13–14; 89:9–10; Dan 7:2–3). The removal of the sea is the permanent elimination of chaos — the creation that God always intended (Gen 1), ordered and good, finally realized without residual disorder.</p>',

    "2": '<p>The new Jerusalem coming down from heaven echoes the heavenly-origin motif of the city-of-God tradition: Paul speaks of "the Jerusalem above" that is free (Gal 4:26); Hebrews speaks of a "heavenly Jerusalem" and a "city that has foundations, whose designer and builder is God" (Heb 11:10, 16; 12:22). The city is not built by human effort but descends as a gift — divine initiative, not human construction. "Prepared as a bride beautifully dressed for her husband" echoes Isa 61:10 ("my soul shall exult in my God, for he has clothed me with garments of salvation... as a bride adorns herself with her jewels") and contrasts pointedly with the whore-city Babylon of ch. 17–18 — both are cities, both are women, but where Babylon was dressed in scarlet and adorned for seduction, Jerusalem is dressed as a bride for covenant fidelity.</p>',

    "3": '<p>"God\'s dwelling place is now among the people" — <em>hē skēnē tou theou meta tōn anthrōpōn</em> (the tent/tabernacle of God with humanity). The language deliberately invokes the tabernacle (<em>skēnē</em>) — the portable sanctuary through which YHWH dwelt with Israel in the wilderness (Exod 40:34–38). The promise runs from Lev 26:11–12 ("I will make my dwelling among you, and my soul shall not abhor you. I will walk among you and will be your God, and you shall be my people") through Ezek 37:27 ("My dwelling place shall be with them, and I will be their God, and they shall be my people") and Zech 2:10–11 to this moment. "They will be his peoples" — the plural (<em>laoi</em>) is significant in some manuscripts: the nations in their diversity become the covenant people of God. "He himself will be with them" adds the personal-presence emphasis beyond mere spatial dwelling.</p>',

    "4": '<p>"He will wipe every tear from their eyes" — the text directly quotes Isa 25:8 ("he will swallow up death forever; and the Lord GOD will wipe away tears from all faces"). Isaiah 25\'s great feast on the mountain, where YHWH destroys death and removes disgrace, is the eschatological template fulfilled here. Isa 35:10 ("everlasting joy shall be upon their heads; they shall obtain gladness and joy, and sorrow and sighing shall flee away") provides further background. The fourfold elimination — no death, no mourning, no crying, no pain — answers the fourfold burden that the fallen creation imposed on human life. "The old order of things has passed away" (<em>ta prōta apēlthan</em>) echoes Isa 43:18–19 ("Remember not the former things, nor consider the things of old. Behold, I am doing a new thing") — the divine re-creation is so complete that the old order is simply past.</p>',

    "5": '<p>"I am making all things new" — the one seated on the throne (the Father) speaks directly for the first time since 1:8. The new creation is his own declaration and action, not a human achievement. "All things new" (<em>panta kaina</em>) picks up the vocabulary of Isa 65:17 and the Pauline new-creation theology (2 Cor 5:17; Gal 6:15). The command "write this down" echoes the commissioning of John at multiple points (1:19; 14:13; 19:9), binding this climactic declaration to the prophetic task of inscribing the revelation. "These words are trustworthy and true" is the divine authentication formula used at Revelation\'s most pivotal declarations (19:9; 21:5; 22:6).</p>',

    "6": '<p>"It is done" (<em>gegonen</em>) echoes 16:17 (the seventh bowl: "It is done!") and points back to John 19:30 (the cross: <em>tetelestai</em>, "It is finished"). The eschatological completion announced at the seventh bowl is now enacted in the new creation. The Alpha-Omega, Beginning-End formula repeats the divine self-declaration of 1:8 and 22:13, framing the entire book between two divine self-identifications. "To the thirsty I will give water from the spring of the water of life without cost" directly quotes Isa 55:1 ("Come, everyone who thirsts, come to the waters; and he who has no money, come, buy and eat!") — the free gift of the life-water is the eschatological fulfillment of Isaiah\'s invitation.</p>',

    "7": '<p>"Anyone who is victorious will inherit all this" — the promise to the victor (<em>ho nikōn</em>) runs through all seven letters of chs. 2–3, each with its own specific promise; now the universal fulfillment is given: inheritance of the new creation itself. "I will be their God and they will be my child" — the covenant formula from Jer 31:33; Ezek 37:27; and Heb 8:10 is reformulated as the adoption formula of 2 Sam 7:14 ("I will be to him a father, and he shall be to me a son") applied universally to the victorious community. The singular <em>huios</em> (son/child) in the Davidic sense reflects the eschatological elevation of all believers to the royal-sonship status that was first promised to David\'s heir.</p>',

    "8": '<p>The catalog of the excluded leads with "the cowardly" (<em>deilos</em>) — a surprising first position. In the context of Revelation, cowardice meant the refusal to witness under persecution, the capitulation to the beast\'s demands rather than suffering martyrdom. The social pressure to participate in imperial cult (trade guilds, civic festivals, household worship) made cowardice a real temptation for the seven churches. The eight-item vice catalog echoes the Mosaic covenant curses (Deut 28:26–68) and the vice lists that mark community boundaries (1 Cor 6:9–10; Gal 5:19–21). "The lake that burns with fire and sulfur" combines the Sodom-judgment imagery (Gen 19:24) with the "second death" identified at 20:14. The catalog creates urgency for the persecuted: endurance in faith is the difference between inheriting the new creation (v. 7) and the second death.</p>',

    "9": '<p>The angel with the bowls — "one of the seven angels who had the seven bowls full of the seven last plagues" — is the same type of guiding angel as the one who showed John the harlot Babylon in 17:1 ("one of the seven angels who had the seven bowls came and said to me, \'Come, I will show you the judgment of the great prostitute\'"). The structural parallel is deliberate: the same angel-type who revealed the harlot-city now reveals the bride-city. The two visions are designed as mirror inversions — where Babylon was the city of seduction and judgment, Jerusalem is the city of covenant fidelity and blessing. The invitation echoes 17:1 nearly verbatim.</p>',

    "10": '<p>"He carried me away in the Spirit to a great and high mountain" — the Spirit-transport to the high mountain for the vision of the restored city echoes Ezek 40:2 precisely ("In visions of God he brought me to the land of Israel and set me down on a very high mountain, on which was a structure like a city to the south"). Ezekiel\'s vision of the restored temple and city (Ezek 40–48) is the primary OT template for the New Jerusalem vision. The great and high mountain also echoes Isa 2:2 ("the mountain of the house of the LORD shall be established as the highest of the mountains") and Isa 40:9 ("Go on up to a high mountain, O Zion, herald of good news"). The descent of the new Jerusalem is seen from the vantage point of the highest perspective.</p>',

    "11": '<p>The glory of God illuminating the city "like a very precious jewel — like a jasper" echoes Ezek 1:26–28 (the divine glory had the appearance of sapphire and the brightness of fire enclosed in a rainbow) and Isa 60:1–3 ("Arise, shine, for your light has come, and the glory of the LORD has risen upon you... nations shall come to your light, and kings to the brightness of your rising"). The jasper-like radiance connects to the divine throne-room vision of 4:3 ("the one seated on the throne had the appearance of jasper and carnelian"). The city shares the very radiance of the enthroned God — the divine glory is not merely present in the city but constitutes the city\'s luminosity.</p>',

    "12": '<p>Twelve gates named for the twelve tribes of Israel — the city\'s gates being named after the tribes fulfills Ezek 48:30–34, where the restored city\'s twelve gates are explicitly named after Israel\'s twelve tribes (three on each of the four sides). Gates named for tribes represent access from the covenant people of every tribe and direction. The twelve angelic gatekeepers echo the Levitical gatekeepers of the temple and its gates (1 Chr 26:1–19; 2 Chr 23:19; Neh 13:22) — the guards at the threshold between holy and profane space, now rendered at eschatological scale.</p>',

    "13": '<p>Three gates on each of the four sides of the city (east, north, south, west) echoes both the layout of Ezekiel\'s restored city (Ezek 48:30–34) and the arrangement of the Israelite camp in the wilderness (Num 2), where the twelve tribes were arranged around the central tabernacle in groups of three per side. The fourfold orientation of access — gates on every side — signals the gathering of the people of God from all directions: Isa 43:5–6 ("I will bring your offspring from the east, and from the west I will gather you; I will say to the north, Give up, and to the south, Do not withhold; bring my sons from afar and my daughters from the end of the earth").</p>',

    "14": '<p>Twelve foundation stones bearing the names of the twelve apostles — the city\'s foundations are the apostolic witness, fulfilling Eph 2:20 ("built on the foundation of the apostles and prophets, with Christ Jesus himself as the cornerstone") and Matt 16:18 ("on this rock I will build my church"). The combination of twelve-tribe gates and twelve-apostle foundations unites the two epochs of the covenant people — Israel and the church — as one eschatological structure. The city is both Jewish (twelve-tribe gates) and apostolic (twelve-apostle foundations): not two separate entities but one building in which the two are architecturally integrated from the ground up.</p>',

    "15": '<p>The golden measuring rod echoes the measuring-rod vision of Ezek 40:3–5 and the measuring of Revelation\'s own temple and city in 11:1–2. In both Ezekiel and Revelation, measuring = divine ownership and protection. The gold of the measuring rod (contrasting with Ezekiel\'s linen-and-reed instrument) signals the eschatological upgrade: the heavenly original is measured directly rather than through an earthly copy. The measurement of "the city, its gates, and its walls" is comprehensive — no part of the city is left outside divine ownership and definition.</p>',

    "16": '<p>The city as a perfect cube — 12,000 stadia in length, width, and height (approximately 1,400 miles in each direction) — is the most architecturally significant detail of the New Jerusalem. The perfect cube shape directly echoes Solomon\'s Holy of Holies: "twenty cubits long, twenty cubits wide, twenty cubits high" (1 Kgs 6:20) — the innermost sanctuary, the zone of unmediated divine presence. The entire New Jerusalem is Holy-of-Holies in scale: where formerly only the high priest could enter the divine presence once a year on Yom Kippur, the whole city is now that space of direct presence for all the redeemed. The number 12,000 multiplies 12 (the complete covenant people) by 1,000 (a symbol of immeasurable fullness).</p>',

    "17": '<p>The wall\'s measurement — 144 cubits — is 12 × 12, the same numerical base as the 144,000 of 7:4–8 (12 × 12 × 1,000). The human/angelic measurement equivalence signals that the heavenly realities are calibrated in human-comprehensible terms. The relative thinness of the wall compared to the city\'s vast dimensions (144 cubits vs. 12,000 stadia = roughly 200 feet vs. 1,400 miles) shows that the wall serves a symbolic function — marking the holy city\'s boundary — rather than a defensive function. The city needs no defensive walls; God himself is its security (Zech 2:4–5: "Jerusalem shall be inhabited as villages without walls... I will be to her a wall of fire all around").</p>',

    "18": '<p>The city built of pure gold "like clear glass" (<em>katharos hyalos</em>) — transparent gold is a material impossibility in ordinary experience, since gold is opaque. The transparency conveys theological meaning: the city in which God dwells has no opacity, no hiddenness, no shadow — everything is visible in the divine light that pervades it. The wall of jasper echoes the jasper-like divine radiance of 4:3 and 21:11 — the wall itself partakes of the divine glory, as if the boundary of the city is formed from the divine radiance rather than from ordinary building material.</p>',

    "19": '<p>The twelve foundation stones decorated with precious stones echo the high priest\'s breastplate (Exod 28:17–20; 39:10–13), which bore twelve precious stones, each engraved with the name of one of the tribes of Israel. The breastplate stones represented all of Israel before God in the priestly intercession; the city\'s foundation stones represent all of Israel-and-the-church in the eschatological city. The specific stones draw on the imagery of Eden (Gen 2:12: gold, bdellium, onyx), the king of Tyre\'s garden (Ezek 28:13: nine precious stones), and Isa 54:11–12 ("I will set your stones in antimony, and lay your foundations with sapphires. I will make your pinnacles of agate, your gates of carbuncles, and all your wall of precious stones") — Isaiah\'s promise to the dishonored wife now enacted for the bride-city.</p>',

    "20": '<p>The continuation of the twelve foundation stones list. Some stone identifications are uncertain due to shifts in ancient gem nomenclature between Hebrew, Greek, and Latin traditions; the LXX translated differently from the Masoretic Text in several cases. The intent is the breastplate-echo pattern rather than a precise gemological catalog. Each stone represents one apostle\'s name on one of the twelve foundations — the church\'s foundational witnesses rendered in permanent, imperishable material. The variety and richness of the stones points to the diversity of the apostolic witness: twelve distinct individuals, twelve distinct stones, one coherent foundation.</p>',

    "21": '<p>Twelve gates each made from a single pearl — a gate of one pearl implies a pearl of cosmological size. Pearls were among the most expensive commodities in the ancient world: the Roman author Pliny records individual pearls worth tens of millions of sesterces; Matt 13:46 uses "a pearl of great value" as an image for the kingdom that demands everything. Gates of single pearls convey inexhaustible, surpassing value — nothing of comparable worth exists in ordinary human commerce. The street of pure gold "as transparent as glass" (cf. v. 18) continues the luminosity-and-transparency theme: the city\'s ground is as translucent as the city\'s walls. The material world of the new creation has become transparent to the divine light that pervades it.</p>',

    "22": '<p>No temple in the city — this is theologically central and demands careful grounding. The entire OT trajectory moved toward the temple as the locus of divine presence: tabernacle (Exod 40) → Solomon\'s temple (1 Kgs 8) → Zerubbabel\'s temple (Ezra 3) → Herod\'s temple (John 2:20) → the eschatological temple (Ezek 40–48). But Revelation\'s New Jerusalem has no temple, because "the Lord God Almighty and the Lamb are its temple." The mediated presence that the temple provided — God dwelling behind the curtain, accessible only through priests and sacrifice — has given way to the immediate, unmediated presence of God and the Lamb as the dwelling-place themselves. The temple was always a means toward the end of direct presence; the city\'s temple-absence makes that direct presence permanent and universal for all the redeemed.</p>',

    "23": '<p>"The glory of God illuminates it, and the Lamb is its lamp" — the fulfillment of Isa 60:19–20 ("The sun shall be no more your light by day, nor for brightness shall the moon give you light; but the LORD will be your everlasting light, and your God will be your glory. Your sun shall no more go down, nor your moon withdraw itself, for the LORD will be your everlasting light, and your days of mourning shall be ended"). Isaiah 60 is Jerusalem\'s great oracle of eschatological glory — the city no longer dependent on created luminaries because the divine glory is its permanent light. The Lamb as the city\'s lamp (<em>lychnos</em>) echoes John 8:12 ("I am the light of the world") and 1:12–16 (Christ walking among the lampstands/churches).</p>',

    "24": '<p>"The nations will walk by its light, and the kings of the earth will bring their splendor into it" — Isa 60:3 ("nations shall come to your light, and kings to the brightness of your rising") and Isa 60:5 ("the abundance of the sea shall be turned to you, the wealth of the nations shall come to you"). The vision of ch. 18 was the kings of the earth lamenting Babylon\'s fall and the merchants weeping over their lost wealth; here the same kings bring their glory (<em>doxa</em>) into the new Jerusalem voluntarily. The Abrahamic promise of blessing to all nations (Gen 12:3; 22:18) is eschatologically enacted: the nations are not destroyed but redeemed and incorporated into the covenant city.</p>',

    "25": '<p>"On no day will its gates ever be shut — for there will be no night there" — Isa 60:11 ("Your gates shall be open continually; day and night they shall not be shut, so that people may bring to you the wealth of the nations, with their kings led in procession"). In the ancient world, city gates were closed at night and in times of threat — open gates marked both security (no enemy to fear) and welcome (unrestricted access). The new Jerusalem needs no defensive closure because God is its total protection. "No night" is the natural consequence of the divine light that makes the sun superfluous (v. 23) — night, which required lamps and closed gates and watchmen, simply does not exist in the city of perpetual divine radiance.</p>',

    "26": '<p>"The glory and honor of the nations will be brought into it" — Isa 60:5, 11, 13 repeated. The nations bring their <em>doxa kai timē</em> (glory and honor), which are the very attributes ascribed to God and the Lamb in the heavenly liturgy (4:11; 5:12–13). What the nations possessed as borrowed glories — the achievements of human civilization, culture, art, learning, governance — are brought as tribute and offering into the city where God is all in all. This vision of cultural redemption (rather than cultural annihilation) has shaped Christian theology of culture throughout history: the new creation is not the erasure of human history but its transformation and incorporation into the divine glory.</p>',

    "27": '<p>"Nothing impure will ever enter it, nor will anyone who does what is shameful or deceitful" — Isa 52:1 ("Awake, awake, put on your strength, O Zion; put on your beautiful garments, O Jerusalem, the holy city; for there shall no more come into you the uncircumcised and the unclean") and Zech 14:21 ("there shall no longer be a trader in the house of the LORD of hosts on that day"). "The Lamb\'s book of life" (cf. 20:15) is the eschatological registry of the redeemed: Exod 32:32–33 (the divine book from which the unfaithful are blotted out); Ps 69:28 ("let them be blotted out of the book of the living"); Dan 12:1 ("everyone whose name shall be found written in the book shall be delivered"); Luke 10:20 ("rejoice that your names are written in heaven"). Inclusion in the new creation depends not on ethnic or ritual qualification but on the divine record of those who belong to the Lamb.</p>'
  },

  "22": {
    "1": '<p>The river of the water of life flowing from the throne — the primary OT template is Ezek 47:1–12, where the man with the measuring rod shows Ezekiel a river flowing from the threshold of the eschatological temple, growing deeper as it flows eastward, bringing life wherever it goes ("everything will live where the river goes," v. 9), with fruit trees on both banks whose leaves do not wither and whose fruit does not fail. The second template is Gen 2:10–14 (the river flowing from Eden branching into four rivers). Revelation\'s river combines both: the eschatological temple-river (Ezekiel) and the primordial garden-river (Genesis), because the new creation restores Eden and fulfills the temple simultaneously. "Flowing from the throne of God and of the Lamb" grounds the source of life not in a created structure but in the co-sovereignty of the Father and Son.</p>',

    "2": '<p>The tree of life on each side of the river bearing twelve fruits (one per month) with leaves for the healing of nations echoes Ezek 47:12 directly ("On the banks, on both sides of the river, there will grow all kinds of trees for food. Their leaves will not wither, nor their fruit fail, but they will bear fresh fruit every month, because the water for them flows from the sanctuary. Their fruit will be for food and their leaves for healing"). The tree of life itself echoes Gen 2:9; 3:22–24, where access was blocked when the cherubim were placed at Eden\'s gate. Access now restored = the exile from Eden reversed. "Leaves for the healing of the nations" extends the tree\'s benefit beyond Israel to universal scope — the Gentile nations included in the eschatological restoration, just as they are included in the great multitude (7:9) and the city (21:24, 26).</p>',

    "3": '<p>"No longer will there be any curse" (<em>katathema</em>) — the reversal of Gen 3:17–19, where the ground was cursed because of Adam\'s sin ("cursed is the ground because of you; in pain you shall eat of it all the days of your life"). The removal of the curse is the completion of creation\'s redemption: not just human beings but the created order itself is healed (Rom 8:19–22: "the creation itself will be liberated from its bondage to decay"). "His servants will serve him" (<em>latreuousin autō</em>) — the verb <em>latreuō</em> carries priestly-service connotations (service in the sanctuary); all the redeemed serve as priests before God, fulfilling Exod 19:6 ("a kingdom of priests and a holy nation") in its fullest eschatological extension.</p>',

    "4": '<p>"They will see his face" — direct vision of the divine face was the supreme eschatological hope and a present impossibility. Exod 33:20 ("you cannot see my face, for man shall not see me and live") established the barrier. The Aaronic blessing ("the LORD make his face shine on you and be gracious to you; the LORD turn his face toward you and give you peace," Num 6:24–26) was the liturgical proxy for direct vision not yet available. Ps 17:15 ("As for me, I shall behold your face in righteousness; when I awake, I shall be satisfied with your likeness") expresses the eschatological hope. Matt 5:8 ("blessed are the pure in heart, for they shall see God") anticipates the beatific vision. In the new Jerusalem, the barrier is permanently dissolved. The divine name on the foreheads (cf. 14:1; 7:3) echoes the high priest\'s forehead-plate engraved with YHWH\'s name (Exod 28:36–38) — all the redeemed now bear what only the high priest formerly wore.</p>',

    "5": '<p>"There will be no more night. They will not need the light of a lamp or the light of the sun, for the Lord God will shine upon them" — Isa 60:19–20 fulfilled (cf. 21:23, 25). The created luminaries and artificial lamps are both superseded. "They will reign forever and ever" (<em>basileusousin eis tous aiōnas tōn aiōnōn</em>) — the redeemed\'s eternal co-reign with God fulfills Dan 7:27 ("the kingdom and the dominion and the greatness of the kingdoms under the whole heaven shall be given to the people of the saints of the Most High; their kingdom shall be an everlasting kingdom") and the promise to the victors throughout chs. 2–3 (2:26–27; 3:21). Ruling is participation in divine governance — the new creation is not static but dynamically ordered by those who share the throne.</p>',

    "6": '<p>"The Lord, the God who inspires the prophets" (<em>ho kyrios ho theos tōn pneumatōn tōn prophētōn</em>, "the God of the spirits of the prophets") — God as the source of prophetic inspiration echoes Num 11:29 ("Would that all the LORD\'s people were prophets, that the LORD would put his Spirit on them"), Zech 1:6, and 1 Cor 14:32 ("the spirits of prophets are subject to prophets"). The angel\'s statement grounds the authority of Revelation\'s prophecy in the same divine Spirit who inspired the OT prophets — Revelation is not a new kind of revelation but the culmination of the same prophetic tradition. "These words are trustworthy and true" repeats the divine authentication of 21:5 and 19:9.</p>',

    "7": '<p>"Behold, I am coming soon" (<em>idou erchomai tachy</em>) — the first of three appearances of this declaration in ch. 22 (vv. 7, 12, 20). The imminence formula does not necessarily mean calendar-imminence but eschatological urgency: the End has been inaugurated with Christ\'s death and resurrection, and the final coming could occur at any moment. "Blessed is the one who keeps the words of the prophecy of this scroll" is the sixth of Revelation\'s seven beatitudes (1:3; 14:13; 16:15; 19:9; 20:6; 22:7; 22:14). The beatitude structure runs throughout the book, each blessing a particular response to the revelation — this one blesses faithful hearing and obedience to the entire prophetic message.</p>',

    "8": '<p>John\'s prostration before the angel echoes the identical scene in 19:10, where the same refusal is given. The repetition is not accidental — it brackets the New Jerusalem vision (chs. 21–22) with the same anti-angel-worship correction that appears before it (19:10), emphasizing that the glorious things John has seen do not transfer their glory to the angelic messenger. The double occurrence reinforces the danger of angel-worship as a live temptation in the early church, consistent with Col 2:18 ("let no one disqualify you, insisting on worship of angels") and the broader trend in Second Temple Judaism where angelology sometimes approached what might be called angelic quasi-worship.</p>',

    "9": '<p>"I am a fellow servant with you and with your brothers the prophets and with all who keep the words of this scroll — worship God" — the angel\'s refusal of worship and self-identification as a fellow servant places angelic and prophetic ministry on the same level of service to the one God. "Worship God" (<em>tō theō proskyněson</em>) is the corrective throughout Revelation — where the beast-system demands worship (13:8, 12, 15), where false religion demands worship of intermediaries, the entire prophetic message redirects to the one God. The angel\'s equality with the prophets positions Revelation\'s angelic mediation within, not above, the community of those who serve God.</p>',

    "10": '<p>"Do not seal up the words of the prophecy of this scroll, because the time is near" — the direct contrast with Dan 12:4 ("But you, Daniel, close the words and seal the book, until the time of the end") is intentional and explicit. Daniel was told to seal his prophecy because its fulfillment was distant; John is told not to seal his because "the time is near" (<em>ho kairos engys estin</em>). Revelation uses this distinction to claim that it belongs to the final epoch of prophetic revelation: what Daniel sealed as future-oriented, Revelation unseals as present-in-fulfillment. The unsealed book is for immediate congregational use — to be read aloud in the churches (1:3), not preserved for later scholarly decoding.</p>',

    "11": '<p>"Let the evildoer still do evil, and the filthy still be filthy, and the righteous still do right, and the holy still be holy" — the formula of irreversibility echoes Ezek 3:27 ("let the one who will hear, hear; and let the one who will refuse, refuse") and Dan 12:10 ("the wicked shall act wickedly. And none of the wicked shall understand, but those who are wise shall understand"). The eschatological urgency creates a paradox: the book is unsealed and its invitation remains open (v. 17: "let the one who is thirsty come"), yet the coming judgment means that character is being fixed in the direction it is already moving. The tension is the tension of the already/not-yet: the judgment is imminent, the opportunity for response is now, and delay courts finality.</p>',

    "12": '<p>"My reward is with me, and I will give to each person according to what they have done" — Isa 40:10 ("Behold, the Lord GOD comes with might, and his arm rules for him; behold, his reward is with him, and his recompense before him") and Isa 62:11 ("Say to the daughter of Zion, \'Behold, your salvation comes; behold, his reward is with him\'"). The divine judge bringing recompense is one of the central OT eschatological images. "According to what they have done" (<em>kata to ergon autou</em>) is the judgment-by-works formula from Ps 62:12; Prov 24:12; Jer 17:10; Matt 16:27; Rom 2:6; 2 Cor 5:10. This does not contradict grace but describes the evidence by which genuine faith is manifested — works are the fruit, not the root, of the life that inherits the new creation.</p>',

    "13": '<p>"I am the Alpha and the Omega, the First and the Last, the Beginning and the End" — the threefold self-identification formula accumulates three pairs: Alpha-Omega (used of the Father in 1:8; applied to Christ here), First-Last (used of Christ in 1:17; 2:8; applied to YHWH in Isa 44:6; 48:12), and Beginning-End (used of the Father in 21:6). The convergence of all three formulas in one declaration signals the theological unity of the Father and Son: what is said of the Father in 1:8 and 21:6 is now said identically of Christ. The divine comprehension of all time — from the first letter to the last, from the beginning point to the end point — is claimed by the returning Lord who authored and will complete the entire story.</p>',

    "14": '<p>"Blessed are those who wash their robes, that they may have the right to the tree of life and may go through the gates into the city" — the seventh and final beatitude of Revelation (cf. 1:3; 14:13; 16:15; 19:9; 20:6; 22:7). Washing robes in the Lamb\'s blood (7:14) = cleansed by the atoning sacrifice; the white robe = righteousness. Access to the tree of life directly reverses Gen 3:22–24 (where access was blocked by the cherubim after the fall). Going through the gates echoes Ps 118:20 ("This is the gate of the LORD; the righteous shall enter through it") — the liturgical entry-gate tradition of Israel\'s worship enacted at the level of the eternal city. The two privileges (tree of life + city entrance) are the supreme goods of chs. 21–22 summarized in one beatitude.</p>',

    "15": '<p>"Outside are the dogs, those who practice sorcery, the sexually immoral, the murderers, the idolaters, and everyone who loves and practices falsehood" — the six excluded categories parallel the eight-item catalog of 21:8, with "dogs" leading. In Deut 23:17–18 (LXX), "dog" refers to male cult prostitutes excluded from Israel\'s assembly; in Phil 3:2 ("beware of the dogs... beware of those who mutilate the flesh") Paul uses it for those who corrupt the gospel. The term carried both cultic-impurity and moral-disgrace connotations. "Everyone who loves and practices falsehood" closes the list with the satanic root-sin (12:9; 20:10: the devil is "the deceiver") — all the excluded categories ultimately express either the love of death or the love of falsehood, the definitional marks of the domain opposed to the God of life and truth.</p>',

    "16": '<p>"I, Jesus, have sent my angel to give you this testimony for the churches. I am the Root and the Offspring of David, and the bright morning star" — Jesus\'s personal authentication of the revelation echoes 1:1 (the chain: God → Christ → angel → John → churches). "The Root and Offspring of David" combines two Davidic claims: Isa 11:10 ("the root of Jesse") and the Davidic-offspring promise; "offspring" connects to the branch/sprout imagery of Isa 11:1; Jer 23:5; Zech 3:8. Jesus is simultaneously David\'s ancestor-Lord (Mark 12:35–37: "How can the scribes say that the Christ is the son of David? David himself... calls him Lord") and David\'s descendant. "The bright morning star" echoes Num 24:17 ("a star shall come out of Jacob") and 2:28 (the promise to the victors: "I will give him the morning star"). The title is self-referential: Christ gives to the victors what he himself is.</p>',

    "17": '<p>"The Spirit and the Bride say, \'Come!\'" — the eschatological invitation issued jointly by the Holy Spirit and the church (the Bride). The double "Come!" has two directions: (1) upward, addressed to the returning Christ ("Come, Lord Jesus!" of v. 20 — the Maranatha prayer); (2) outward, addressed to the thirsty ("let the one who is thirsty come"). This bidirectional invitation is the church\'s defining eschatological posture: simultaneously praying for the parousia and extending the gospel invitation to the world. "Let the one who is thirsty come — let the one who desires take the water of life without cost" quotes Isa 55:1 ("Come, everyone who thirsts, come to the waters... come, buy wine and milk without money and without price") — the Isaianic free-offer of the eschatological feast is now the church\'s standing invitation.</p>',

    "18": '<p>"If anyone adds anything to them, God will add to that person the plagues described in this scroll" — the warning against addition echoes Deut 4:2 ("You shall not add to the word that I command you, nor take from it") and Deut 12:32 ("Everything that I command you, you shall be careful to do. You shall not add to it or take from it"). The application of the Deuteronomic Torah-formula to Revelation positions the book as having the binding authority of divinely given Torah — not replacing Scripture but completing it. The penalty for addition uses the book\'s own content (the plagues of Revelation) as the punishment — the Word is self-enforcing. This formula also appeared in ancient treaty documents as a curse against those who alter treaty texts, giving the warning both scriptural and cultural resonance for the first-century audience.</p>',

    "19": '<p>"If anyone takes words away from this scroll of prophecy, God will take away from that person any share in the tree of life and in the holy city" — the removal penalty (losing access to the tree of life and the city) is the reversal of the book\'s climactic promises: the tree of life (22:2, 14) and the holy city (21:2, 10) are the ultimate goods Revelation describes. To tamper with the book is to forfeit the goods it promises. The warning continues the Deuteronomic formula of v. 18 — adding earns the plagues, subtracting loses the blessings. The symmetry of the paired warnings (add/subtract; earn plagues/lose blessings) reflects the covenantal structure of Deuteronomy 27–28 (curses for disobedience, blessings for obedience) applied to the prophetic text itself.</p>',

    "20": '<p>"Yes, I am coming soon. Amen. Come, Lord Jesus!" — the closing exchange between the risen Christ and the community contains the Aramaic liturgical formula Maranatha, preserved in 1 Cor 16:22 ("If anyone has no love for the Lord, let him be accursed. Maranatha!") and the Didache 10.6 ("Let grace come and this world pass away. Hosanna to the God of David. If anyone is holy, let him come; if anyone is not so, let him repent. Maranatha. Amen"). The Aramaic origin (the vernacular of early Palestinian Christianity) proves this was a pre-Pauline liturgical prayer used at the Lord\'s Supper — the earliest Christian communities were already praying for the Lord\'s return in the context of the eucharistic meal. Revelation ends by placing itself within that living liturgical tradition: the book is read aloud at worship and the congregation responds with the ancient prayer for the parousia.</p>',

    "21": '<p>"The grace of the Lord Jesus be with God\'s people. Amen" — the standard Pauline letter-closing benediction (Rom 16:20; 1 Cor 16:23; 2 Cor 13:14; Gal 6:18; Eph 6:24; Phil 4:23; 1 Thess 5:28; 2 Thess 3:18; Titus 3:15; Phlm 25) applied to Revelation confirms that the book belongs to the letter-genre as well as the apocalyptic-prophetic genre (cf. 1:4–6: the letter opening to the seven churches). Grace (<em>charis</em>) is the defining gift of the new covenant — the unmerited divine favor that the book has chronicled from the throne-room to the new Jerusalem — and it is the last word before the "Amen." The revelation that began with grace "from him who is and who was and who is to come" (1:4) ends with the grace of the Lord Jesus: both the triune source and the incarnate mediator of grace are named; the community that receives it is named "God\'s people" — the covenant relationship that was the thread of all Scripture is the final word.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'revelation')
    merge_comm(existing, REVELATION)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'revelation', existing)
    print('Revelation 21–22 mkt-context written.')

